\begin_layout Abstract
We study a recently
\emph on
 
\emph default
proposed new cosmological phase where a scalar field moves periodically
 in an expanding spatially-flat Friedmann universe.
 This phase corresponds to a limit cycle of the equations of motion and
 can be considered as a cosmological realization of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time-crystal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 We show that this phase is only possible, provided the Null Energy Condition
 is violated and the so-called Phantom Divide is crossed.
 We prove that in general k-essence models: i) this crossing causes infinite
 growth of quantum perturbations on short scales, and ii) exactly periodic
 solutions are only possible, provided the limit cycle encircles a singularity
 in the phase plane.
 The configurations neighboring this singular curve in the phase space are
 linearly unstable on one side of the curve and superluminal on the other
 side.
 Moreover, the increment of the instability is infinitely growing for each
 mode by approaching the singularity, while for the configurations on the
 other side, the sound speed is growing without limit.
 We illustrate our general results by analytical and numerical studies of
 a particular class of such k-essence models.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually the appearance of a periodic structure in space is attributed to
 formation of ordinary crystals.
 By analogy, the authors of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shapere:2012nq"

\end_inset

 suggested to use the name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time-crystals
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the systems with vacuum solutions which are exactly periodic in time.
 In cosmology such vacuum solutions can be interesting in context of Dark
 Energy and early stages of Inflation.
 On the quantum level this idea was further elaborated in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wilczek:2012jt"

\end_inset

.
 However, a cosmological expansion usually works as a friction and dissipates
 energy, so that an exactly periodic motion is impossible.
 Indeed, a usual system will finally approach an equilibrium static configuratio
n with minimal energy density.
 However, in some non-canonical cases, the lowest possible available configurati
on can still be non-static and correspond to a motion.
 In particular, this is the case for the ghost condensate 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ArkaniHamed:2003uy"

\end_inset

.
 This is also the basis for the original k-inflation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ArmendarizPicon:1999rj"

\end_inset

 attractor.
 Thus the solution with the lowest energy level can spontaneously break
 the time-translation invariance.
 Due to the shift-symmetry of the ghost condensate, this spontaneous symmetry
 breaking still results there in the time-independent and Lorentz-invariant
 energy momentum tensor (EMT).
 The latter corresponds to the normal de Sitter vacuum with some cosmological
 constant.
 It is rather interesting to consider wether one can spontaneously break
 time-translational invariance even on the level of the EMT so that the
 vacuum configuration is different from the de Sitter spacetime.
 Here we mean that this non-trivial solution should be valid for very long
 times up to the asymptotic future.
 In particular, if the motion in this vacuum state is periodic, with the
 period 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

, then the continuous time translation invariance, 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow t+c$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 real, is only broken to the level of a discrete subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow t+n\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is an integer.
 The recent work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bains:2015gpv"

\end_inset

 proposed an interesting new phase of cosmological matter with these properties.
 In this phase a scalar field periodically moves in the constantly expanding
 universe.
 This oscillatory phase was realized by a non-canonical scalar field theory
 of the k-essence type 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ArmendarizPicon:1999rj,ArmendarizPicon:2000ah,ArmendarizPicon:2000dh,Chiba:1999ka"

\end_inset

, see the next section for details.
 A similar idea of an oscillating dark energy was studied in e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Feng:2004ff,Nojiri:2006ww"

\end_inset

.
 While quasi-periodic oscillations and their finite duration in non-minimally
 coupled scalar-tensor theories with a canonical kinetic term were considered
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Arefeva:2012sqa,Skugoreva:2014gka,Pozdeeva:2016cja"

\end_inset

.
 On top of that a periodically evolving universe with the positive spatial
 curvature was in the focus of the works 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Harrison:1967zz,1990MNRAS.243..252K"

\end_inset

.
 Later in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dabrowski:1995ae,Graham:2011nb"

\end_inset

 it was showed that these solutions can be realized by a canonical scalar
 field with negative potential.
 In this paper we discuss weather it is possible to realize a time-crystal
 in a spatially-flat cosmological setup with a minimally coupled k-essence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
NEC violation is needed for a limit cycle 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A presence of exactly periodic motion with the period 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

, in particular, requires that the energy density is periodic 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\left(t+\mathcal{T}\right)=\varepsilon\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 the energy density was decreasing, then somewhere between 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 the energy density should start to increase to compensate this reduction.
 And vice versa: for the originally increasing energy density there should
 be a moment between 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 where the energy density should start to decrease.
 Thus anyway during each cycle there are time intervals on which the energy
 density is growing and on which it is decreasing.
 Further, the conservation of energy in a Friedmann universe requires 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{\varepsilon}=-3H\left(\varepsilon+p\right)\,,\label{eq:energy_conservation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the Hubble parameter and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the effective pressure of the oscillatory matter.
 Hence, in an expanding universe (with 
\begin_inset Formula $H>0$
\end_inset

) the energy density can grow, only if the effective enthalpy density 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon+p$
\end_inset

 is negative.
 The negative sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon+p$
\end_inset

 implies a violations of the Null Energy Condition (NEC) which states that
 for all null vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 the energy-momentum tensor should satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}n^{\mu}n^{\nu}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 In turn, a violation of the NEC necessarily implies that the Hamiltonian
 density of the system is unbounded from below - for each constant there
 are such local values of the initial data that the energy density is more
 negative than this constant, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sawicki:2012pz"

\end_inset

.
 In other words a violation of NEC implies that the system has to possess
 configurations with arbitrary negative energy densities.
 For a recent discussion of NEC violation see e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rubakov:2014jja"

\end_inset

.
 Clearly, in a collapsing universe, a decrease in energy density would require
 an NEC violation as well.
 In cosmology, matter which violates NEC is often referred to as Phantom
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Caldwell:1999ew"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, the time derivative of the energy density can change
 the sign, provided 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 changes sign.
 In this case the spatially-flat Friedmann universe has to be able to evolve
 from expansion to contraction and then from contraction to expansion.
 The latter transition corresponds to a bounce.
 It is well known that a bounce of a spatially-flat Friedmann universe requires
 a violation of NEC.
 Indeed, the transition from contraction to expansion at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{b}$
\end_inset

 requires 
\begin_inset Formula $H\left(t_{b}\right)=\dot{a}/a=0$
\end_inset

.
 Using the Friedmann equations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H^{2}=\frac{1}{3}\varepsilon\,,\label{eq:Friedmann_1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Except of the last section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Particular_Model"

\end_inset

 we use the reduced Planck units with 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\text{Pl}}=\left(8\pi G_{\text{N}}\right)^{-1/2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{H}=-\frac{1}{2}\left(\varepsilon+p\right)\,,\label{eq:Friedmann_2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we obtain that at transition from contraction with 
\begin_inset Formula $H<0$
\end_inset

 to expansion with 
\begin_inset Formula $H>0$
\end_inset

 one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{H}>0$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon+p<0$
\end_inset

 so that NEC is violated again.
 Hence we conclude that a violation of NEC is necessary to realize an exactly
 periodic oscillatory cosmological phase.
 Moreover, due to the periodicity the system should be able to evolve through
 the so-called Phantom Divide (PD) - the border of the NEC-violating region.
 This border corresponds to the equation of state parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $w=p/\varepsilon=-1$
\end_inset

.
 The dynamical transition through 
\begin_inset Formula $w=-1$
\end_inset

 should cyclicly happen in both directions from above and from below.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is well known that systems of k-essence type cannot dynamically violate
 NEC and cross the Phantom Divide 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vikman:2004dc"

\end_inset

, see also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hu:2004kh,Caldwell:2005ai,Xia:2007km"

\end_inset

 and for the review 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cai:2009zp,Nesseris:2006er"

\end_inset

.
 Note that the pathologies associated with the crossing of the Phantom Divide
 are more severe than those problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hsu:2004vr,Buniy:2005vh,Buniy:2006xf,Dubovsky:2005xd,Abramo:2005be"

\end_inset

 arising just due to the violation of NEC.
 Below in the next section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "sec:Refreshing-k-essence-and"

\end_inset

 we will refresh some basic facts about k-essence and provide simple arguments
 against a smooth transition of a k-essence field through the Phantom Divide.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally it is useful to consider the average of 
\begin_inset Formula $w+1$
\end_inset

 over some time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $T=t_{f}-t_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:energy_conservation"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Friedmann_1"

\end_inset

 under the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f}$
\end_inset

 we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle w\left(t\right)+1\right\rangle _{T}=\frac{1}{T}\int_{t_{i}}^{t_{f}}dt\left(1+w\left(t\right)\right)=-\frac{1}{T}\int_{t_{i}}^{t_{f}}dt\frac{\dot{\varepsilon}}{\varepsilon\sqrt{3\varepsilon}}=\frac{1}{T}\sqrt{\frac{4}{3}}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{\varepsilon\left(t_{f}\right)}}-\frac{1}{\sqrt{\varepsilon\left(t_{i}\right)}}\right)\,.
\]

\end_inset

If the time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of the period of oscillations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle w\left(t\right)+1\right\rangle _{T}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus such an oscillatory stage can be interesting to model inflation and
 dark energy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Refreshing k-essence and why cannot it cross the Phantom Divide
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Refreshing-k-essence-and"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we will collect and discuss basic mostly well known facts about k-essence
 which is a noncanonical, minimally coupled to gravity scalar field whose
 dynamics is described by the action 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\int d^{4}x\,\sqrt{-g}\,p\left(\varphi,X\right)\,,\label{eq:action_general}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X=\frac{1}{2}g^{\mu\nu}\varphi_{,\mu}\varphi_{,\nu}\,.\label{eq:X}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In cosmological applications the field is only slightly inhomogeneous and
 anisotropic so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{,\mu}$
\end_inset

 is timelike, hence throughout the paper we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X>0$
\end_inset

, as our signature convention 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+,-,-,-\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This class of theories was introduced in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ArmendarizPicon:1999rj"

\end_inset

 (see also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ArmendarizPicon:2000dh,ArmendarizPicon:2000ah,Chiba:1999ka"

\end_inset

).
 The corresponding EMT is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\mu\nu}=p_{,X}\varphi_{,\mu}\varphi_{,\nu}-pg_{\mu\nu}\,,\label{eq:EMT_General}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for every timelike 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{,\mu}$
\end_inset

 this EMT takes a form of a perfect fluid 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\mu\nu}=\left(\varepsilon+p\right)u_{\mu}u_{\nu}-pg_{\mu\nu}\,,\label{eq:EMT_Fluid}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the four velocity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{\mu}=\frac{\varphi_{,\mu}}{\sqrt{2X}}\,,\label{eq:Velocity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and the energy density 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon=2Xp_{,X}-p.\label{eq:Energy_density}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence for all null vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\mu\nu}n^{\mu}n^{\nu}=p_{,X}\left(\varphi_{,\mu}n^{\mu}\right)^{2}=\frac{\varepsilon+p}{2X}\left(\varphi_{,\mu}n^{\mu}\right)^{2}\,.\label{eq:NEC_k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The Null Energy Condition requires 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}n^{\mu}n^{\nu}\geq0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,X}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus to change the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}n^{\mu}n^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 the system has to change the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,X}$
\end_inset

 or for time-like derivatives to change the sign of the enthalpy density
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon+p$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if the transition is smooth, then at the Phantom Divide
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Around any time-like, 
\begin_inset Formula $X>0$
\end_inset

, background (in particular around cosmological backgrounds 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garriga:1999vw"

\end_inset

) the perturbations propagate with the speed given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{\text{S}}^{2}=\left(\frac{\partial p}{\partial\varepsilon}\right)_{\varphi}=\frac{p_{,X}}{\varepsilon_{,X}}\,.\label{eq:sound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The small perturbations of k-essence around any background propagate in
 an effective (contravariant) metric 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Babichev:2007dw"

\end_inset

 which is conformally equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{\mu\nu}=p_{,X}g_{\mu\nu}+p_{,XX}\varphi_{,\mu}\varphi_{,\nu}\,,
\]

\end_inset

see also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Babichev:2007dw,ArmendarizPicon:2005nz,Bruneton:2006gf,Bruneton:2007si"

\end_inset

, see also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Moncrief:1980,Bilic:1999sq"

\end_inset

 for the relativistic acoustic geometry in closely related irrotational
 perfect fluids.
 The equation of motion is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G^{\mu\nu}\nabla_{\mu}\nabla_{\nu}\varphi+\varepsilon_{,\varphi}=0\,.\label{eq:covariant_equation_of_motion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The positivity of the right hand side of the expression 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:sound"

\end_inset

 guaranties that this equation of motion is a hyperbolic quasilinear PDE.
 Note that hyperbolicity guaranties that Cauchy problem is well posed and
 evolution is predictable till some moment of time.
 However, it was demonstrated that breakdown of predictability due to the
 formation of caustics is a rather generic phenomenon, see recent discussion
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Babichev:2016hys,Mukohyama:2016ipl,deRham:2016ged,Tanahashi:2017kgn"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Most recently it was speculated 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Babichev:2017lrx"

\end_inset

 that k-essence could be UV completed by a canonical complex scalar U(1)
 field.
 This UV completion would eliminates the formation of caustics as a problem.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In cosmology the equation of motion reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon_{,X}\ddot{\varphi}+3H\dot{\varphi}p_{,X}+\varepsilon_{,\varphi}=0\,,\label{eq:equation_of_motion_cosmology}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is given by the first Friedmann equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Friedmann_1"

\end_inset

 with the energy density 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Energy_density"

\end_inset

.
 Instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 one can use 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 as independent variables.
 In this case the Jacobian is 
\begin_inset Formula $J=p_{,\varphi}\varepsilon_{,\dot{\varphi}}-\varepsilon_{,\varphi}p_{,\dot{\varphi}}$
\end_inset

.
 The dynamical equation on energy density is 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:energy_conservation"

\end_inset

 with the Hubble parameter given by the first Friedmann equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Friedmann_1"

\end_inset

.
 While the dynamical equation for the pressure is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{p}=-\frac{1}{\varepsilon_{,X}}\left(6XHp_{,X}^{2}+p_{,\varphi}\varepsilon_{,\dot{\varphi}}-\varepsilon_{,\varphi}p_{,\dot{\varphi}}\right)\,,\label{eq:derivative_of_pressure}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the Hubble parameter is expressed through the energy density by the
 first Friedmann equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Friedmann_1"

\end_inset

 and all other quantities should be expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\varepsilon,p\right)$
\end_inset

 using implicit function theorem.
 Unfortunately this description is only valid outside of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}=0$
\end_inset

 line.
 Indeed, the Jacobian can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J=p_{,\varphi}\varepsilon_{,\dot{\varphi}}-\varepsilon_{,\varphi}p_{,\dot{\varphi}}=\dot{\varphi}\left(p_{,\varphi}\varepsilon_{,X}-\varepsilon_{,\varphi}p_{,X}\right)\,,
\]

\end_inset

where the right hand side is vanishing on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}=0$
\end_inset

 line.
 However, if a limit cycle exists, it has to cross this line.
 Thus the Jacobian is not sign-definite and it is not clear whether the
 expression in the brackets of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:derivative_of_pressure"

\end_inset

 is sign-definite.
 For a shift-symmetric case (with the symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\rightarrow\varphi+c$
\end_inset

) the pressure evolves due to the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:energy_conservation"

\end_inset

.
 In this case a limit cycle is not possible in an expanding universe, because
 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}p_{,X}\propto a^{-3}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}p_{,X}$
\end_inset

 always decreasing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further it is useful to use the energy conservation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:energy_conservation"

\end_inset

 along with the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Friedmann_1"

\end_inset

 and the definition of energy density 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Energy_density"

\end_inset

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\frac{4}{3}\varepsilon_{f}}-\sqrt{\frac{4}{3}\varepsilon_{i}}=\int_{\varepsilon_{i}}^{\varepsilon_{f}}\frac{d\varepsilon}{\sqrt{3\varepsilon}}=-\int_{t_{i}}^{t_{f}}dt\dot{\varphi}p_{,\dot{\varphi}}=-\int_{\varphi_{i}}^{\varphi_{f}}d\varphi\,p_{,\dot{\varphi}}\,.
\]

\end_inset

If the motion is periodic we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\oint\,d\varphi\,p_{,\dot{\varphi}}=0\,.
\]

\end_inset

The later condition we can transform using the Green's formula to and the
 expression for the energy density 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Energy_density"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\oint\,d\varphi\,p_{,\dot{\varphi}}=-\iint d\varphi d\dot{\varphi}\,p_{,\dot{\varphi}\dot{\varphi}}=-\iint d\varphi d\dot{\varphi}\,\varepsilon_{,X}=0\,.\label{eq:Integral_from_energy_cons}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}$
\end_inset

 has to change the sign and have this opposite sign on some area inside
 of the limit cycle.
 We will obtain the same result in a different way later in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:General-phase-space"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Momentum invertibility and strong superluminality 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further it is illuminating to look at the canonical formulation of the dynamics.
 It is particularly useful as the authors of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bains:2015gpv"

\end_inset

 are interested in degenerate Hamiltonians which are not smooth functions
 of canonical momenta.
 For smooth Lagrangians this happens when the field velocity cannot be uniquely
 expressed through the canonical momentum.
 We will proceed using the ADM formalism, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Arnowitt:1962hi"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Poisson"

\end_inset

.
 In a spacetime foliation generated by a time-like congruence with a tangent
 vector 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 we can represent the metric as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ds^{2}=N^{2}dt^{2}-\ell_{ik}\left(dx^{i}+N^{i}dt\right)\left(dx^{k}+N^{k}dt\right)\,.
\]

\end_inset

The unit normal to the hypersurface of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{\mu}=N\partial_{\mu}t\,.
\]

\end_inset

The relative three velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the k-essence fluid velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 (given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Velocity"

\end_inset

) can be found from 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-v^{2}}}=U_{\mu}u^{\mu}=Nu^{t}=\frac{1}{N\sqrt{2X}}\left(\dot{\varphi}-N^{i}\varphi_{,i}\right)\,,\label{eq:relative_velocity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v^{2}=1-\frac{2XN^{2}}{\left(\dot{\varphi}-N^{i}\varphi_{,i}\right)^{2}}\,,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

so that after some algebra 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v^{2}=\frac{N^{2}\ell^{ik}\varphi_{,i}\varphi_{,k}}{\left(\dot{\varphi}-N^{i}\varphi_{,i}\right)^{2}}\,,\label{eq:relative_v}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we have used the standard ADM results 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{ik}=-\ell^{ik}+N^{i}N^{k}/N^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{ti}=-N^{i}/N^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{tt}=1/N^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell^{ik}\ell_{km}=\delta_{m}^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The canonical momentum is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P=\frac{\partial}{\partial\dot{\varphi}}\left(\sqrt{-g}p\right)=\sqrt{-g}p_{,X}\frac{1}{N^{2}}\left(\dot{\varphi}-N^{i}\varphi_{,i}\right)\,.\label{eq:momentum}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence, the canonical momentum is always vanishing at the crossing of the
 Phantom Divide 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 can be found from the canonical momentum provided
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial P}{\partial\dot{\varphi}}\neq0\,.\label{eq:solvability_momentum}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In cosmology this momentum is 
\begin_inset Formula $P=a^{3}\dot{\varphi}p_{,X}$
\end_inset

 and cannot be 
\emph on
locally
\emph default
 expressed exclusively through 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $a\left(t\right)=\exp\left(\int^{t}dt'\sqrt{\varepsilon\left(\varphi\left(t'\right),\dot{\varphi}\left(t'\right)\right)/3}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Using the definitions of the relative velocity 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:relative_v"

\end_inset

 and the sound speed 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:sound"

\end_inset

 this invertibility condition (for a given scale factor 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, before solving the Hamiltonian constraint - the first Friedmann equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Friedmann_1"

\end_inset

) can be written in the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial P}{\partial\dot{\varphi}}=\sqrt{-g}\left(\left(u^{t}\right)^{2}2Xp_{,XX}+p_{,X}g^{tt}\right)=\sqrt{-g}G^{tt}=\frac{\varepsilon_{,X}}{N}\sqrt{\ell}\left(\frac{1-v^{2}c_{\text{S}}^{2}}{1-v^{2}}\right)\,.\label{eq:invertability}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In particular, one can chose such a foliation that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is constant on the equal-time hypersurface, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In this foliation 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

 and the invertibility of the momentum requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Note that а cusp Hamiltonian and non-invertibility of momentum are among
 the desirable features of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time crystals
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and one of the requirements imposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bains:2015gpv"

\end_inset

 on a general system with an oscillatory attractor as a ground state.
 Indeed, the ground state implies a minimum of the Hamiltonian.
 But if all first derivatives of the Hamiltonian are vanishing, there is
 no motion and an oscillatory configuration cannot be a ground state.
 Clearly for systems with cusp Hamiltonians this argument does not work.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the homogeneous and isotropic cosmological dynamics of a k-essence
 scalar field driving the expansion of the universe cannot be brought to
 this simple two dimensional canonical form.
 Below, in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:General-phase-space"

\end_inset

, using standard results from the theory of ODE, we prove that the changing
 of sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}$
\end_inset

 is a necessary condition for the existence of cosmological limit cycles.
 Hence one has to require that on some configurations 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

.
 But, for a generic k-essence Lagrangian, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

 does not imply 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, for 
\begin_inset Formula $X>0$
\end_inset

 and a finite and non-vanishing 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,X}$
\end_inset

 the singular surface where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the divergent speed of sound for the perturbations 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{S}}^{2}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}$
\end_inset

 changes sign (as required for the existence of a limit cycle) it implies
 that on one side of the singular hypersurface there is a region of extreme
 superluminality, while the configurations on the other side suffer from
 infinitely strong gradient instabilities.
 On these latter configurations 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{S}}^{2}<0$
\end_inset

 and the equation of motion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:covariant_equation_of_motion"

\end_inset

 becomes an elliptic quasilinear PDE.
 Thus generically these 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time crystals
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 k-essence systems require existence of configurations with an infinitely
 strong superluminality which are neighboring configurations with infinitely
 strong gradient instabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As it follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:derivative_of_pressure"

\end_inset

 the pressure has an infinite time derivative at the singularity.
 Thus the time derivative of the Ricci scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 blows up as well.
 An effective action in gravity should contain the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\partial R\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 which blows up in this case.
 This is another way to see that EFT breaks down on the singular curve where
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As it follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:invertability"

\end_inset

, for superluminal speeds of sound the invertibility of the momentum-velocity
 relation can be also violated on a foliation with the relative velocity
 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}=1/c_{\text{S}}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case the hypersurface of constant time coincides with the characteristi
c surface of the equation of motion.
 Clearly such a surface cannot be chosen for initial data and the foliation
 is not suitable for the Cauchy problem.
 For a detailed discussion see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Adams:2006sv,Babichev:2007dw"

\end_inset

.
 Other works discussing the non-uniqueness of the Hamiltonian due to the
 multivalued relation between momentum and field velocity include 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aharonov:1969vu,Henneaux:1987zz,Rizos:2012qs"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Classical and quantum perturbations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further the cosmological scalar perturbations are described by the action
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\frac{1}{2}\int d\eta d^{3}x\,Z\left(\left(\mathcal{R}'\right)^{2}-c_{\text{S}}^{2}\left(\partial_{i}\mathcal{R}\right)^{2}\right)\,,\label{eq:action for perturbations}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is the conformal time and the curvature perturbation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

 is constructed out of the perturbation of the k-essence field 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\varphi$
\end_inset

 and the Newtonian potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}=\Phi+H\frac{\delta\varphi}{\dot{\varphi}}\,,\label{eq:curvature_perturbation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where both perturbations are written in terms of gauge-invariant variables
 which correspond to the Newtonian gage.
 Finally the normalization is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z=a^{2}\left(\frac{\varepsilon+p}{c_{\text{S}}^{2}H^{2}}\right)=\varepsilon_{,X}\left(\frac{\dot{\varphi}a}{H}\right)^{2}\,.\label{eq:Normalization}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The action is ghosty provided 
\begin_inset Formula $Z<0$
\end_inset

 which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}<0$
\end_inset

.
 If NEC is violated, but there are no gradient instabilities so that the
 system is hyperbolic and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{S}}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

, then necessarily 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}<0$
\end_inset

 and the action is ghosty.
 Ghost instabilities are perturbative, but rely on interactions with other
 fields.
 In particular there is always an interaction through gravity.
 On the contrary the gradient instabilities are linear short scale instabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

 at the Phantom Divide then the background solution has to go through a
 singularity of the equation of motion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:equation_of_motion_cosmology"

\end_inset

.
 For example it is the case in the example provided in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nojiri:2006ww"

\end_inset

.
 Even if we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{S}}$
\end_inset

 remains nonzero and does not blow up one would need to guaranty that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,\varphi}/\varepsilon_{,X}$
\end_inset

 does not blow up.
 However, in that case 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,\varphi}$
\end_inset

 should vanish at the same point where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}$
\end_inset

 is vanishing.
 This provides two equations in the phase space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\varphi,\dot{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 to satisfy.
 Therefore this can generically only happen on isolated points of the measure
 zero corresponding to extrema of the energy density.
 This degenerate case was in details discussed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vikman:2004dc"

\end_inset

.
 Another crucial point is that at the Phantom Divide with non-vanishing
 speed of sound the normalization factor 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is vanishing.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=0$
\end_inset

 corresponds to an infinitely strong coupling on all scales at for the QFT
 of perturbations.
 Indeed, the cubic terms in the action for perturbations contain higher
 order derivatives of the background quantities and are not vanishing at
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=0$
\end_inset

.
 A QFT which only contains third order operators is strongly coupled on
 all scales.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to understand the pathology is to introduce the canonical variable
 (Mukhanov-Sasaki variable) which for for k-essence is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garriga:1999vw,Mukhanov:2005sc"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v=z\mathcal{R}\,,\label{eq:canonical}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z=\frac{a\dot{\varphi}}{H}\left|\frac{\varepsilon+p}{2Xc_{\text{S}}^{2}}\right|^{1/2}=\frac{a\dot{\varphi}}{H}\,\sqrt{\left|\varepsilon_{,X}\right|}\,.
\]

\end_inset

The canonical variable can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v=a\sqrt{\left|\varepsilon_{,X}\right|}\left(\delta\varphi+\Phi\frac{\dot{\varphi}}{H}\right)\,.\label{eq:canonical_longer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The dynamics of this variable is described by the action 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\frac{1}{2}\sigma\int d\eta d^{3}x\left(\left(v'\right)^{2}+c_{\text{S}}^{2}v\Delta v+\frac{z''}{z}v^{2}\right)\,,\label{eq:action_Canonical}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\mbox{sign}\left(\varepsilon_{,X}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding dispersion relation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega_{k}^{2}=c_{\text{S}}^{2}k^{2}-\frac{z''}{z}\,,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $-z''/z$
\end_inset

 plays the role of the square of effective time-dependent mass.
 Positive 
\begin_inset Formula $z''/z$
\end_inset

 indicates the Jeans instability operating on large scales where one cannot
 neglect expansion of spacetime.
 This mass is infinitely growing (in the positive or negative direction)
 at the Phantom Divide with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly this does not allow to separate scales and treat the perturbations
 as an EFT.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another problem is rooted in the speed of sound.
 Let's now assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}>0$
\end_inset

 at the Phantom Divide.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{S}}^{2}\left(t_{pd}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and by continuity 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{S}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 changes sign at this point.
 This change of sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{S}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 implies the transition of the equation of motion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:covariant_equation_of_motion"

\end_inset

 from the hyperbolic to the elliptic type of PDE or vice versa.
 It is well known that the Cauchy problem is ill-posed for elliptical PDE's.
 The problem is in the short wavelength instabilities behaving as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta\varphi_{\mathbf{k}}\sim\exp\left(\left|c_{\text{S}}\mathbf{k}\right|t\right)\,,\label{eq:grrowth}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that the increment of instability in mode 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|c_{\text{S}}\mathbf{k}\right|$
\end_inset

 and grows for large wave numbers without any bound.
 In reality the bound is provided by a lattice size or by the strong coupling
 scale.
 In both these cases the instability has a characteristic scale corresponding
 to the cut off scale completely destroying the predictability of the theory.
 If a system enters the elliptic regime on a classical solution which is
 in the formal region of validity of the EFT, than the system stays there
 much longer than the inverse frequency cut off scale.
 In that case all physical modes get a tremendous exponential amplification
 due to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:grrowth"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth looking at the quantum fluctuations to understand the problem.
 If we start from a healthy background 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{S}}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}>0$
\end_inset

, then in a Hadamard state (short scales vacuum state) the mode functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}$
\end_inset

 for the canonical variable 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:canonical_longer"

\end_inset

 are normalized inside the horizon (for scales 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{S}}k\ll\left|z''/z\right|$
\end_inset

) as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|v_{k}\right|=\sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{\omega_{k}}}\simeq\sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{c_{\text{S}}k}}\,.\label{eq:mode_func_norm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where we have explicitly written 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

 to stress the quantum origin of this quantity.
 Then the characteristic quantum fluctuation of the canonical variable on
 scale 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta v_{k}\sim\sqrt{\hbar}\left|v_{k}\right|k^{3/2}\sim\sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{c_{\text{S}}}}\,k\,.\label{eq:fluctuations}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

On these ultrashort physical length scales 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=a/k$
\end_inset

 we can neglect the fluctuations of the Newtonian potential (see below)
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta\varphi_{\ell}\sim\sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{\varepsilon_{,X}c_{\text{S}}}}\left(\frac{k}{a}\right)=\left(\frac{\hbar^{2}}{\varepsilon_{,X}p_{,X}}\right)^{1/4}\cdot\frac{1}{\ell}=\left(\frac{2X\hbar^{2}}{\varepsilon_{,X}\left(\varepsilon+p\right)}\right)^{1/4}\cdot\frac{1}{\ell}\,.\label{eq:field_quantum_fluctuation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here we assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\gg L_{UV}$
\end_inset

, where the latter is the UV-cutoff length scale which is typically present
 in such derivatively coupled theories.
 Thus if either of the quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,X}$
\end_inset

 is vanishing, the quantum fluctuations 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\varphi_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 blow up on short scales.
 In particular, for 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{S}}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 quantum fluctuations at every given scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 inside the horizon blow up and completely invalidate the applicability
 of the whole theory of cosmological perturbations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand the fluctuations of the Newtonian potential on short scales
 are scale-independent 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Phi_{\ell}\sim\sqrt{\hbar}\left(\frac{\varepsilon+p}{c_{\text{S}}}\right)^{1/2}\sim\sqrt{\hbar}\left(X\varepsilon_{,X}\left(\varepsilon+p\right)\right)^{1/4}\,,
\]

\end_inset

see page 345 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mukhanov:2005sc"

\end_inset

.
 These fluctuations are always small provided 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{S}}\gtrsim\varepsilon+p$
\end_inset

.
 The latter condition can also be written in standard units as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{\text{S}}\gtrsim\left(\frac{\varepsilon}{\varepsilon_{\text{Pl}}}\right)\left(1+w\right)\,,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{\text{Pl}}$
\end_inset

 is the Planckian energy density
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Clearly this is is a rather weak lower bound on the sound speed for a dust-like
 k-essence.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 It is worthwhile to compare the right hand side of this expression with
 the Ricci curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $R=-\varepsilon\left(1-3w\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The magnitude of the quantum fluctuations 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\varphi_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 on a short scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 can be also obtained from the following uncertainty relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta\varphi_{\ell}\cdot\delta P_{\ell}\gtrsim\hbar\,\ell^{-3}\,,\label{eq:uncirtainty}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta P_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 is the fluctuation of the canonical momentum on this scale, for a detailed
 discussion see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vikman:2012bx"

\end_inset

.
 Further, the canonical momentum of fluctuations is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta P_{\ell}=G^{tt}\delta\dot{\varphi}_{\ell}=\varepsilon_{,X}\delta\dot{\varphi}_{\ell}\,.
\]

\end_inset

The fluctuation of the field velocity on short-scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 can be estimated as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta\dot{\varphi}_{\ell}\simeq\omega_{\ell}\delta\varphi_{\ell}\simeq\left(c_{\text{S}}/\ell\right)\delta\varphi_{\ell}\,.
\]

\end_inset

For an oscillator the vacuum saturates the uncertainty relation therefore
 for a collection of oscillators 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta\varphi_{\ell}^{2}\simeq\frac{\hbar}{\varepsilon_{,X}c_{\text{S}}}\cdot\frac{1}{\ell^{2}}\,,
\]

\end_inset

which again gives 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:field_quantum_fluctuation"

\end_inset

.
 This estimation is not applicable, if the system is strongly coupled for
 scales 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{S}}k\lesssim\left|z''/z\right|$
\end_inset

.
 However, in that case the predictive power of such theory is rather limited.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, these results above imply that it is physically impossible
 to avoid a singularity and to bounce a spatially-flat Friedmann universe
 just using the k-essence.
 Though it is not very hard to find a corresponding bouncing cosmological
 solution in k-essence, e.g see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Abramo:2007mp,DeSantiago:2012nk"

\end_inset

 and for the most recent discussion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fertig:2016czu,Romano:2016jlz"

\end_inset

.
 There are two ways out.
 Either one should assume that k-essence perturbations can receive large
 corrections from spatial higher derivatives (HD), thereby curing the situation
 without spoiling the bouncing background, as was done in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Creminelli:2006xe,Creminelli:2007aq"

\end_inset

.
 In this case it is not entirely clear whether spatial HD can be dominant
 in effective field theories just on the perturbative level.
 For the most recent discussion of an extension of k-essence by HD operators
 and NEC violation, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "deRham:2017aoj"

\end_inset

.
 Another possibility is to try more general theories with one degree of
 freedom but with covariant HD in the total action.
 The latter strategy to arrange a stable bounce free from ghosts and gradient
 instabilities was followed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Qiu:2011cy,Easson:2011zy"

\end_inset

.
 Before that a possibility to have a healthy bouncing solution in such theories
 was very briefly mentioned without any proof or further discussion in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Creminelli:2010ba"

\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Easson:2011zy"

\end_inset

