\begin_layout Section
General phase space analysis and the Bendixson–Dulac theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:General-phase-space"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cosmological equation of motion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:equation_of_motion_cosmology"

\end_inset

 can be written in the first order form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \frac{d\dot{\varphi}}{dt}=-3Hc_{\text{S}}^{2}\dot{\varphi}-\frac{\varepsilon_{,\varphi}}{\varepsilon_{,X}}\,,\label{eq:first_order_system_norm}\\
 & \frac{d\varphi}{dt}=\dot{\varphi}\,.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

The first equation of this system above is singular for configurations with
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The integral curves for the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\dot{\varphi},\ddot{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 of on the phase space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\varphi,\dot{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d\dot{\varphi}}{d\varphi}=-3Hc_{\text{S}}^{2}-\frac{\varepsilon_{,\varphi}}{\varepsilon_{,\dot{\varphi}}}\,.\label{eq:integral_curves}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For every k-essence with the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\varphi,\dot{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 it is convenient to introduce an auxiliary system of ODE 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vikman:2004dc"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \frac{du}{dt}=\alpha\left(u,v\right)=-p_{,u}\sqrt{3\varepsilon}-\varepsilon_{,v}\,,\label{eq:auxiliarly_system}\\
 & \frac{dv}{dt}=\beta\left(u,v\right)=\varepsilon_{,u}\,,\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=up_{,u}-p$
\end_inset

.
 Without the friction term 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,u}\sqrt{3\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 these ODEs are the Hamilton equations of motion with canonical momentum
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Without this friction term the motion happens on the curves of constant
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,u}=up_{,X}$
\end_inset

, the effective friction coefficient is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,X}\sqrt{3\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

.
 If the sign of the friction coefficient is always positive the dissipative
 motion cannot be periodic.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,X}$
\end_inset

 has to change the sign for the existence of a limit cycle.
 This is a reformulation of the same statement presented in at the beginning
 of the paper.
 This system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system"

\end_inset

 is different from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:equation_of_motion_cosmology"

\end_inset

, but it is constructed out of the same function 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\varphi,\dot{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 where instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 one plugs in 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 one plugs in 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 The solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 are different from 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{v}\neq u$
\end_inset

.
 The main point is that this system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system"

\end_inset

 has the same integral curves on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v,u\right)$
\end_inset

 as the equation of motion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:equation_of_motion_cosmology"

\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\varphi,\dot{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

, but it is clearly less singular.
 These integral curves are locally given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:integral_curves"

\end_inset

.
 In particular a limit cycle corresponds to a closed integral curve on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\varphi,\dot{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 plane and on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v,u\right)$
\end_inset

 plane.
 Тhe time flow in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v,u\right)$
\end_inset

 goes in the opposite direction to the time flow in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\varphi,\dot{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 for the regions with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}<0$
\end_inset

 as both first order equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 have an opposite sign to the corresponding equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:first_order_system_norm"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nontrivial fixed points
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Nontrivial-fixed-points"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of the friction, one can expect, that the (non-degenerate) fixed
 points of the system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system"

\end_inset

 should always be saddles, nodes and foci.
 However, nontrivial fixed points with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

 can only be either saddles or centers.
 Let us prove this statement.
 Note that these fixed points of the auxiliary system are located on the
 singular curve of the original system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:first_order_system_norm"

\end_inset

.
 Around a generic fixed point
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\delta v=\varepsilon_{,uu}\delta u+\varepsilon_{,uv}\delta v\,,
\]

\end_inset

and for a nontrivial fixed point at which 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\delta u=-\left[p_{,uv}\sqrt{3G_{\text{N}}\varepsilon}+\frac{3G_{\text{N}}}{2}p_{,u}\frac{\varepsilon_{,v}}{\sqrt{3G_{\text{N}}\varepsilon}}+\varepsilon_{,vv}\right]\delta v-\varepsilon_{,vu}\delta u\,,
\]

\end_inset

where we have used 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,u}=\varepsilon_{,X}u=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,uu}=\left(up_{,X}\right)_{,u}=p_{,X}+2Xp_{,XX}=\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If we further use 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(u,v\right)=-p_{,u}\sqrt{3G_{\text{N}}\varepsilon}-\varepsilon_{,v}=0$
\end_inset

, the last equation takes the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\delta u=p_{,u}\left[\frac{3}{2}G_{\text{N}}p_{,u}-\left(\frac{\varepsilon_{,v}}{p_{,u}}\right)_{,v}\right]\delta v-\varepsilon_{,vu}\delta u\,.
\]

\end_inset

Hence for the eigenvalues of the linearized system we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda^{2}=\varepsilon_{,uv}^{2}+\varepsilon_{,uu}p_{,u}\left[\frac{3}{2}G_{\text{N}}p_{,u}-\left(\frac{\varepsilon_{,v}}{p_{,u}}\right)_{,v}\right]\,.\label{eq:Nontrivial_Eigenvalue}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These eigenvalues are either both real and of opposite sign, so that the
 fixed point is a saddle, or both eigenvalues are purely imaginary so that
 the fixed point is a center in the linear approximation.
 Thus a fixed point on the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

 cannot be a node.
 By virtue of the Lyapunov theorem, for a fixed point to be an exact center,
 a nonlinear system has to posses an analytic non-trivial integral of motion
 around this fixed point.
 The latter requirement is rather strong and can only be realized in special
 cases.
 Hence one can expect that the center in linear approximation should become
 a non-linear focus.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Bendixson–Dulac theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This theorem states that, if there exist a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(u,v\right)$
\end_inset

 (called the Dulac function) such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\left(f\alpha\right)}{\partial u}+\frac{\partial\left(f\beta\right)}{\partial v}>0\,,
\]

\end_inset

almost everywhere in a simply connected region of the plane, then there
 are no periodic solutions lying entirely within the region.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further we will assume that in the region where of phase space where the
 limit cycle is located the energy density is strictly positive, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 This is needed for the differentiability of the right hand side of the
 system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, this excludes a possibility of a bounce happening in this region
 of phase space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In that case one can chose the Dulac function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\varepsilon\right)=1/\sqrt{3\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 for which we have
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is important to stress the power of the Dulac generalization of the original
 Bendixson theorem which only allowed for 
\begin_inset Formula $f=1$
\end_inset

.
 In that case one would obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}\left(3\varepsilon+p\right)$
\end_inset

 should change the sign for the existence of the limit cycle.
 This is clearly a weaker requirement.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\left(f\alpha\right)}{\partial u}+\frac{\partial\left(f\beta\right)}{\partial v}=\left(-f\left(\varepsilon\right)p_{,u}\sqrt{3\varepsilon}\right)_{,u}=-\varepsilon_{,X}\,,
\]

\end_inset

where we have used that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,uu}=\left(up_{,X}\right)_{,u}=p_{,X}+2Xp_{,XX}=\varepsilon_{,X}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the system should necessary possess a singularity where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}$
\end_inset

 changes sign or at least vanishing.
 Otherwise the limit cycle cannot exist.
 This goes beyond the statement that the limit cycle should have a fixed
 point of the system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system"

\end_inset

 inside.
 Indeed, for a fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,u}=\varepsilon_{,X}u$
\end_inset

 should vanish.
 The latter is always realized at the origin where 
\begin_inset Formula $u=0$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the change of sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}$
\end_inset

 is a strong requirement for the existence of a limit cycle.
 It is not clear whether this condition can be obtained just form the requiremen
t that the sign of the time-derivative of the pressure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:derivative_of_pressure"

\end_inset

 should change.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cosmocanonical equations 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 does not correspond to a naive 
\emph on
flat space
\emph default
 canonical momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=\partial\mathscr{L}/\partial\dot{\varphi}=p_{,\dot{\varphi}}=P/a^{3}$
\end_inset

 for the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, for this momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 we obtain using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:equation_of_motion_cosmology"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{\pi}=-3H\pi+\left(\frac{\partial p}{\partial\varphi}\right)_{\dot{\varphi}}\,,\label{eq:fake_canonical}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 instead of the first equation of the auxiliary system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system"

\end_inset

.
 From this equation above it follows that on the limit cycle the 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,\varphi}$
\end_inset

 (taken by constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}$
\end_inset

) should change the sign.
 Thus a limit cycle crosses the curve on phase space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\varphi,\dot{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,\varphi}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, otherwise it is impossible to overcome the Hubble friction and
 the
\emph on
 flat space
\emph default
 canonical momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 would always decrease in an expanding universe.
 Note that the transition to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is not that useful in the region with a singularity 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

, as there the relation between momentum and field velocity becomes not
 invertible, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:invertability"

\end_inset

.
 Thus this description would not be useful to prove the statement that this
 singularity is required for a limit cycle.
 Now we can look at the 
\emph on
flat space
\emph default
 Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{H}=\dot{\varphi}\pi-p\,.\label{eq:another_Hamiltonian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Clearly this Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:another_Hamiltonian"

\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 by value, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\left(u,v\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}\left(\varphi,\pi\right)$
\end_inset

 are two different functions.
 Further using 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{\partial p}{\partial\varphi}\right)_{\pi}=\left(\frac{\partial p}{\partial\varphi}\right)_{\dot{\varphi}}+\left(\frac{\partial p}{\partial\dot{\varphi}}\right)_{\varphi}\left(\frac{\partial\dot{\varphi}}{\partial\varphi}\right)_{\pi}\,,
\]

\end_inset

we get that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{\partial p}{\partial\varphi}\right)_{\dot{\varphi}}=-\left(\frac{\partial\mathcal{H}}{\partial\varphi}\right)_{\pi}\,,
\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fake_canonical"

\end_inset

 differs from the canonical equation by a friction term with
\emph on
 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $3H=\sqrt{3\mathcal{H}}$
\end_inset

 friction coefficient.
 The first order equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 does not have the friction term and remains canonical 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{\varphi}=\left(\frac{\partial\mathcal{H}}{\partial\pi}\right)_{\varphi}\,.
\]

\end_inset

Contrary to the auxiliary system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system"

\end_inset

 the trajectories in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\varphi,\pi\right)$
\end_inset

 are not identical to the integral curves of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:equation_of_motion_cosmology"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can start from the system 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \dot{\pi}=-\sqrt{3\mathcal{H}}\,\pi-\mathcal{H}_{,\varphi}\,,\label{eq:almoust_Hamilton_equations}\\
 & \dot{\varphi}=\mathcal{H}_{,\pi}\,,\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

and use the Bendixson–Dulac theorem with the Dulac function 
\begin_inset Formula $f=1/\sqrt{3\mathcal{H}}$
\end_inset

 to obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\pi}\left(f\alpha\right)+\partial_{\varphi}\left(f\beta\right)=-1$
\end_inset

.
 Which implies that the limit cycle is not possible, provided the conditions
 of the Bendixson–Dulac theorem are satisfied.
 In particular, the relevant assumption there was that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(\varphi,\pi\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\left(\varphi,\pi\right)$
\end_inset

 are smooth - i.e.
 that the flat space Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 is smooth.
 Hence a limit cycle is not possible for k-essence with a smooth Hamiltonian.
 Moreover, one can expect that the 
\emph on
cosmocanonical
\emph default
 system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:almoust_Hamilton_equations"

\end_inset

 is universal – holds for 
\emph on
any generic
\emph default
 cosmological scalar field 
\emph on
beyond
\emph default
 k-essence i.e.
 Galileons, Horndeski theories etc 
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We assume here that the system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:almoust_Hamilton_equations"

\end_inset

 is valid for a cosmological scalar field with a second order covariant
 equation of motion.
 A detailed discussion will be provided somewhere else.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Therefore we expect that the limit cycle in an expanding universe is only
 possible for systems with a not smooth flat space Hamiltonian.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Phase space analysis of the particular model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Particular_Model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we provide a detailed phase space analysis of the class
 of k-essence systems discussed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bains:2015gpv"

\end_inset

.
 This analysis will mostly serve for the illustrative purposes of our generic
 results obtained above.
 It is also interesting in view of the results from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cai:2017dyi"

\end_inset

, where it was claimed that one can model a geodesically complete healthy
 bounce with a background solution given entirely by a k-essence model,
 whereas the perturbations can be made healthy because of the additional
 beyond-Horndeski terms from DHOST 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Langlois:2015cwa,Langlois:2015skt"

\end_inset

 present in the action.
 Similar constructions of the healthy bounce in DHOST were presented in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Creminelli:2016zwa"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kolevatov:2017voe"

\end_inset

, though there the background evolution is not driven purely by a k-essence.
 The limit cycle is a geodesically complete solution with, or as we studied
 here, without bounces of the scale factor.
 Hence one can hope that similar beyond-Horndeski terms may stabilize the
 limit cycle without substantial changes in the background dynamics considered
 here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expansion of the universe will be assumed to be driven by the scalar
 field itself through the first Friedmann equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Friedmann_1"

\end_inset

.
 The Lagrangian studied in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bains:2015gpv"

\end_inset

 is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(\varphi,X)=\left(3b\,\varphi^{2}-1\right)X+X^{2}-V\left(\varphi\right)\,,\label{eq:kosc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the double-well potential is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V\left(\varphi\right)=\Lambda+\frac{1}{12a}-\frac{1}{2}\varphi^{2}+\frac{3a}{4}\varphi^{4}\,.\label{eq:potential}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To make all quantities dimensionless we use units of some mass scale 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, whose square otherwise would appear in front of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{2}$
\end_inset

 operator in the potential above.
 It is reasonable to assume that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\ll M_{\text{Pl}}\,.
\]

\end_inset

As we will show later it is a correct assumption, see Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Physical_Energy_Density_Last"

\end_inset

.
 Otherwise we will assume that all parameters of the Lagrangian, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 are typically 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Without potential and with 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

 this system corresponds to simple k-inflation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ArmendarizPicon:1999rj"

\end_inset

 and ghost condensate 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ArkaniHamed:2003uy"

\end_inset

.
 The authors only considered 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset

, which we will assume in this paper as well along with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 The extrema of the potential are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\varphi_{0}=0\,, & \:\varphi_{\pm}=\pm\frac{1}{\sqrt{3a}}\,.\label{eq:Fixed_Points}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Thus in the phase space of the homogeneous solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\varphi,\dot{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 there are always three equilibrium points - fixed points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0\right)\,,\left(\pm1/\sqrt{3a},0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly the first trivial point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0\right)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a false vacuum which is unstable.
 There 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\varphi_{0}\right)=\Lambda+1/\left(12a\right)$
\end_inset

.
 While the fixed points with symmetry breaking, the true vacua, correspond
 to de Sitter solutions with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(\varphi_{\pm}\right)=\Lambda\,.
\]

\end_inset

The NEC is violated when 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,X}<0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 inside of the Phantom Divide (PD) which is given by the ellipse 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{\varphi}^{2}+3b\,\varphi^{2}=1\,.\label{eq:NEC_ellipse}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 outside of the ellipse the system does not violate the NEC.
 On the ellipse the equation of state 
\begin_inset Formula $w=-1$
\end_inset

.
 From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:field_quantum_fluctuation"

\end_inset

 it follows that by approaching the PD ellipse from outside the quantum
 perturbations on short scales diverge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The corresponding energy density is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Energy_density"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon=\left(3b\,\varphi^{2}-1\right)X+3X^{2}+V\left(\varphi\right)\,.\label{eq:particular_energy_density}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The singularity in the equation of motion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:equation_of_motion_cosmology"

\end_inset

 occurs when 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

 or on the ellipse 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
3\dot{\varphi}^{2}+3b\,\varphi^{2}=1\,.\label{eq:Singularity_ellipse}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:field_quantum_fluctuation"

\end_inset

 it follows that by approaching this singularity ellipse with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=0$
\end_inset

 from inside the quantum perturbations on short scales diverge.
 Note that both ellipses 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NEC_ellipse"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Singularity_ellipse"

\end_inset

 share the same 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 axis, but the axis in 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 for the PD is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{3}$
\end_inset

 times larger then the axis of teh singularity ellipse.
 Hence the singularity 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Singularity_ellipse"

\end_inset

 is located inside of the PD 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NEC_ellipse"

\end_inset

 for arbitrary positive 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the sound speed 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:sound"

\end_inset

 as a function on phase space we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{\text{S}}^{2}\left(\varphi,\dot{\varphi}\right)=\frac{\dot{\varphi}^{2}+3b\,\varphi^{2}-1}{3\dot{\varphi}^{2}+3b\,\varphi^{2}-1}=1-\frac{2\dot{\varphi}^{2}}{3\dot{\varphi}^{2}+3b\,\varphi^{2}-1}\,.
\]

\end_inset

Thus for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}=3\dot{\varphi}^{2}+3b\,\varphi^{2}-1<0$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 inside of the singularity ellipse 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Singularity_ellipse"

\end_inset

 the sound speed is always superluminal except of points 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}=0$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}>0$
\end_inset

 the speed of sound is never superluminal.
 By approaching this singular ellipse 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Singularity_ellipse"

\end_inset

 from inside the sound speed grows without any limit.
 It is important that configurations with superluminality are separated
 from a possible limit cycle by the singularity ellipse 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Singularity_ellipse"

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, no physically relevant trajectory can cross this border 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vikman:2004dc"

\end_inset

, while we know that the limit cycle (if exists) has to cross the Phantom
 Divide 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NEC_ellipse"

\end_inset

 which is located outside of the singularity ellipse.
 In the region of the phase space between the PD 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NEC_ellipse"

\end_inset

 and the singularity ellipse 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Singularity_ellipse"

\end_inset

 the sound speed is imaginary and the equation of motion (including perturbation
s) is an elliptic PDE.
 The increment of this linear instability grows for each mode without any
 bound by approaching the singularity ellipse 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Singularity_ellipse"

\end_inset

.
 The linear instability for high 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 modes was mentioned in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bains:2015gpv"

\end_inset

, albeit the authors used a different formula for the sound speed.
 Namely it was assumed that one can treat the system as a perfect fluid
 so that the sound speed can be inferred from 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{s}^{2}=\partial\left\langle p\right\rangle /\partial\left\langle \varepsilon\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 where the averaging is done over many oscillations.
 Clearly this formula is different from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:sound"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand for the derivative of the energy density we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{,\varphi}=\varphi\left(3b\dot{\varphi}^{2}+3a\varphi^{2}-1\right)\,.
\]

\end_inset

Thus there is also an ellipse of the vanishing 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,\varphi}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
3b\dot{\varphi}^{2}+3a\varphi^{2}=1\,.\label{eq:zero_force_ellipse}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As we have showed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "sec:General-phase-space"

\end_inset

 a limit cycle has to pass through configurations where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{,\varphi}=0$
\end_inset

.
 This is not a strong requirement as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{,\varphi}=\varphi\left(3b\dot{\varphi}^{2}+1-3a\varphi^{2}\right)\,,
\]

\end_inset

and the limit cycle can just evolve through 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=0$
\end_inset

 which is anyway required by the symmetry of the system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our further analysis of the phase curves it is convenient to use the
 auxiliary system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system"

\end_inset

 in phase space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v,u\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For the system under consideration 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:kosc"

\end_inset

 auxiliary system is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \frac{du}{dt}=-p_{,u}\sqrt{3G_{\text{N}}\varepsilon}-\varepsilon_{,v}=-u\left(3bv^{2}+u^{2}-1\right)\sqrt{3G_{\text{N}}\varepsilon}-v\left(3av^{2}+3bu^{2}-1\right)\,,\label{eq:auxiliarly_system_concrete_example}\\
 & \frac{dv}{dt}=\varepsilon_{,u}=u\left(3bv^{2}+3u^{2}-1\right)\,,\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the energy density is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:particular_energy_density"

\end_inset

 with the substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\rightarrow v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}\rightarrow u$
\end_inset

 : 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon\left(v,u\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(3b\,v^{2}-1\right)u^{2}+\frac{3}{4}u^{4}+\Lambda+\frac{1}{12a}-\frac{1}{2}v^{2}+\frac{3a}{4}v^{4}\,,\label{eq:energy_density_uv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the dimensionless Newtons constant is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{\text{N}}=\frac{m^{2}}{M_{\text{Pl}}^{2}}\,.
\]

\end_inset

Under the natural assumptions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{\text{N}}\ll1\,.
\]

\end_inset

The advantage of this auxiliary system is that the singular ellipse 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Singularity_ellipse"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,u}=0$
\end_inset

, does not correspond to a singularity anymore.
 In generic case when 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq b\neq1$
\end_inset

 the dynamical flow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}=\left(\dot{v},\dot{u}\right)$
\end_inset

 across the singular ellipse is parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

-axis, see the right plot on Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "fig:Limit_2"

\end_inset

 for a degenerate case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For small 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 or close to the 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

-axis the flow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

 is always pointing outside of the singular ellipse, as the positive cosmologica
l friction term 
\begin_inset Formula $-p_{,X}u\sqrt{3G_{\text{N}}\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 dominates.
 However, by approaching the 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

-axis along the singular ellipse the second term in the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system_concrete_example"

\end_inset

 starts to dominate, as 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is vanishing.
 And the direction of flow changes inwards.
 On the singular ellipse, the points of equilibrium between these two forces
 on the right hand side of the first equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system_concrete_example"

\end_inset

 are nontrivial fixed points of the auxiliary system.
 As we discussed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Nontrivial-fixed-points"

\end_inset

 such fixed points can be either a saddle or a center (at the linear approximati
on).
 Due to the symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v,u\right)\rightarrow\left(-v,-u\right)$
\end_inset

 of the system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system_concrete_example"

\end_inset

 there are always at least two such nontrivial fixed points.
 Thus the system has at least five fixed points in total, on top of those
 located at infinity.
 We will study this issue later in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Fixed-points"

\end_inset

 in more details.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Energy Density 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is convenient to express the energy density in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\frac{1}{2}u^{2}\:\:\text{and}\:\:Y=\frac{1}{2}v^{2}\,,
\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon\left(X,Y\right)=3X^{2}+3aY^{2}+6bXY-X-Y+\Lambda+\frac{1}{12a}\,.
\]

\end_inset

This quadratic form has an extremum at 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{m}=\frac{1}{6}\left(\frac{a-b}{a-b^{2}}\right)\:\:\text{and}\:\:Y_{m}=\frac{1}{6}\left(\frac{1-b}{a-b^{2}}\right)\,.\label{eq:extremum_XY}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This extremum exists in real 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

either if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b<1\:\:\text{and}\:\:a\geq b\,,
\]

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b>1\:\:\text{and}\:\:a\leq b\,,
\]

\end_inset

or for the special case when 
\begin_inset Formula $b=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

.
 In this extremum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{m}=\varepsilon\left(X_{m},Y_{m}\right)=\Lambda-\frac{\left(a-b\right)^{2}}{12a\left(a-b^{2}\right)}\,.
\]

\end_inset

The matrix of second derivatives has the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon''=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\varepsilon_{,XX} & \varepsilon_{,XY}\\
\varepsilon_{,XY} & \varepsilon_{,YY}
\end{array}\right)=6\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & b\\
b & a
\end{array}\right)\,.
\]

\end_inset

This matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon''$
\end_inset

 is positive-definite, provided 
\begin_inset Formula $a>b^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In that case extremum 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:extremum_XY"

\end_inset

 is a minimum which for real 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 can only exist for 
\begin_inset Formula $b\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 In this case requiring that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{m}=\Lambda-\frac{\left(a-b\right)^{2}}{12a\left(a-b^{2}\right)}>0\,,
\]

\end_inset

 is sufficient to guaranty that the the equation of motion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system_concrete_example"

\end_inset

 has analytic right hand side, so that our analysis accomplished in the
 previous sections can be applicable in the whole phase space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v,u\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fixed Points
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Fixed-points"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now study the fixed points in more details.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
False Vacuum: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start from the trivial fixed point, the false vacuum where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(u,v\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 In that case 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon\left(v,u\right)=\Lambda+\frac{1}{12a}+\mathcal{O}\left(u^{2},v^{2}\right)\equiv\frac{V_{0}}{G_{\text{N}}}+\mathcal{O}\left(u^{2},v^{2}\right)\,,
\]

\end_inset

so that the linearized system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system_concrete_example"

\end_inset

 takes the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \frac{du}{dt}=u\sqrt{3V_{0}}+v\,,\label{eq:Origin_Fixed}\\
 & \frac{dv}{dt}=-u\,,\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

with the corresponding eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{\pm}^{f}=\sqrt{\frac{3V_{0}}{4}}\pm\sqrt{\frac{3V_{0}}{4}-1}\,.
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}\geq4/3$
\end_inset

 both eigenvalues are real and positive so that the fixed point is an unstable
 node.
 While for 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}<4/3$
\end_inset

 both roots are complex with a positive real part so that the fixed point
 is an unstable focus.
 In both cases continuum of trajectories originate from the trivial fixed
 point.
 The Poincar
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
'
\end_layout

\end_inset

e index of this false vacuum is 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\text{N}}=0$
\end_inset

 this point is a center.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
True Vacua: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us consider other fixed points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\pm\left(3a\right)^{-1/2},0\right)$
\end_inset

 which are the true vacua of the potential.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

 these fixed points are located outside of the PD and of the Singularity.
 In this case the Lagrangian starts around them from the usual kinetic term
 and these points are indeed stable true vacua.
 Whereas for 
\begin_inset Formula $b<a$
\end_inset

 these fixed points are inside of these ellipses, the Lagrangian starts
 with the wrong-sing kinetic term, and the system behaves as a ghost condensate
 with potential.
 In this case these points should be unstable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the energy we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon=\Lambda+\mathcal{O}\left(\delta u^{2},\delta v^{2}\right)\,,
\]

\end_inset

so that the linearized system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system_concrete_example"

\end_inset

 takes the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \frac{du}{dt}=-u\left(\frac{b}{a}-1\right)\sqrt{3G_{\text{N}}\Lambda}-2\delta v\,,\label{eq:nontrivial_fixed_point}\\
 & \frac{d\delta v}{dt}=u\left(\frac{b}{a}-1\right)\,.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

The corresponding eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{\pm}^{t}=\frac{\sqrt{3G_{\text{N}}\Lambda}}{2}\left[\left(1-\frac{b}{a}\right)\pm\sqrt{\left(1-\frac{b}{a}\right)^{2}+\frac{8}{3G_{\text{N}}\Lambda}\left(1-\frac{b}{a}\right)}\right]\,.\label{eq:eigenvalues_true_vacuum}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Further we will neglect the fine-tuned and degenerate case when 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b$
\end_inset

 so that the true vacua are located on the Singularity.
 We only consider simple fixed points where the linear analysis is applicable,
 for this degenerate case see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "fig:Limit_2"

\end_inset

.
 Both eigenvalues are real provided either 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a>b\,,\label{eq:true_vac_saddle}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b>a\left(1+\frac{8}{3\Lambda G_{\text{N}}}\right)\,.\label{eq:true_vac_node}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 In the first case 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:true_vac_saddle"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{+}^{t}>0$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{-}^{t}<0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence both these fixed points are saddle points in this case.
 Thus in this case the true vacua are inside of the PD and the Singularity
 and they are always unstable saddle points with the Poincar
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
'
\end_layout

\end_inset

e index -1.
 In the second case the true vacua are outside the PD and the Singularity
 and separated from them at least by the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3a\right)^{-1/2}\left(1-\left(1+8/\left(3\Lambda G_{\text{N}}\right)\right)^{-1/2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In this case both roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\pm}^{t}$
\end_inset

 are negative, so that and the true vacua are stable nodes with the Poincar
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
'
\end_layout

\end_inset

e index +1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In-between these two ranges of parameters namely when 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1<\frac{b}{a}<1+\frac{8}{3\Lambda G_{\text{N}}}\,,\label{eq:true_vac_focus}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that the true vacua are relatively not far outside of the the PD and
 the Singularity, and these fixed points are stable foci with the Poincar
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
'
\end_layout

\end_inset

e index +1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\text{N}}=0$
\end_inset

 the eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{\pm}^{t}=\pm\sqrt{2\left(1-\frac{b}{a}\right)}\,.
\]

\end_inset

Hence, for vanishing Newton constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

 both true vacua are centers, whereas for 
\begin_inset Formula $b<a$
\end_inset

 these points are inside of the Singularity and they are saddles and therefore
 unstable.
 For this reason one cannot consider them as a really true vacua in this
 case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Nontrivial Fixed Points 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We should study the equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-u\left(3bv^{2}+u^{2}-1\right)\sqrt{3G_{\text{N}}\varepsilon}=v\left(3av^{2}+3bu^{2}-1\right)=\varepsilon_{,v}\,,
\]

\end_inset

on the singularity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u^{2}=\frac{1}{3}-bv^{2}\,,\label{eq:u_on_singularity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}<\left(3b\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 For small 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\text{N}}$
\end_inset

 the only way to compensate the small friction term is to have comparably
 small force 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,v}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have to look for such solutions of this equation that the force
 is vanishing as 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\text{N}}^{1/2}$
\end_inset

.
 For the normal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 there can be two neighborhoods when this can happen: either around 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

 or around a possible root of 
\begin_inset Formula $3av^{2}+3bu^{2}-1$
\end_inset

, provided the later is located at the interval of interest.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence on the singularity the zero-force ellipse in the auxiliary system
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:auxiliarly_system_concrete_example"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{,v}=v\left(3av^{2}+3bu^{2}-1\right)=v\left(3v^{2}\left(a-b^{2}\right)+b-1\right)\,.
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
3v^{2}\left(a-b^{2}\right)+b-1>0\,,
\]

\end_inset

around the fixed point, then in the nontrivial fixed points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v_{*},u_{*}\right)$
\end_inset

 the first component 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{*}$
\end_inset

 has the same sign as the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
3v^{2}\left(a-b^{2}\right)+b-1<0\,,
\]

\end_inset

around the fixed point, then in the nontrivial fixed points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v_{*},u_{*}\right)$
\end_inset

 the first component 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{*}$
\end_inset

 has the sign opposite to sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The force vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{zf}^{2}=\frac{b-1}{3\left(b^{2}-a\right)}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{zf}^{2}=\frac{b-1}{3\left(b^{2}-a\right)}<\frac{1}{3b}\,,
\]

\end_inset

then the force changes sign on the projection of the singularity on to 
\begin_inset Formula $v-$
\end_inset

axes.
 The last inequality corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
b<1 & \text{and} & a>b\,,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
b>1 & \text{and} & a<b\,.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

For the maximal 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\left(3b\right)^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 the force term 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,v}$
\end_inset

 has the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nontrivial fixed points are roots of the following polynomial equation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{P}\left(v_{*}^{2}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \mathscr{P}\left(v_{*}^{2}\right)=-\frac{\left(a-b\right)^{2}}{3b^{3}}+\left(2+\frac{1-2a}{b}-\frac{4a}{b^{2}}+\frac{3a^{2}}{b^{3}}\right)v_{*}^{2}-3\left(b+2-\frac{4a}{b}-\frac{2a}{b^{2}}+\frac{3a^{2}}{b^{3}}\right)v_{*}^{4}+\\
 & +\left[\frac{9a^{2}}{b^{3}}-\frac{18a}{b}+9b+G_{\text{N}}\left(\frac{1}{a}+\frac{a}{b^{2}}-\frac{2}{b}+12\Lambda\right)\right]v_{*}^{6}+\frac{6}{b}G_{\text{N}}\left[1-\frac{a}{b}\right]v_{*}^{8}+9G_{\text{N}}\left[\frac{a}{b^{2}}-1\right]v_{*}^{10}\,.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Small roots vanishing in decoupling.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we can search for the root close to 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial equation above has the following approximate root 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & v_{s}^{2}=G_{\text{N}}\,\frac{1}{27}\left[\frac{12\Lambda+\left(a^{-1}-1\right)}{\left(b-1\right)^{2}}\right]\times\label{eq:Nontrivial_root}\\
 & \times\left[1-G_{\text{N}}\,\frac{b(b-3)+2a^{2}\left(12\Lambda-1\right)+ab\left(7-3b+12\left(b-3\right)\Lambda\right)}{9a\left(b-1\right)^{3}}+\mathcal{O}\left(G_{N}^{2}\right)\right]\,,\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

which satisfies this equation up to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(G_{N}^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 inclusively and vanishes in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\text{N}}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 For the existence of this root one has to require only the positivity of
 the energy density on the Singularity close to the 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon\left(0,\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\right)=\Lambda+\frac{1}{12a}-\frac{1}{12}\geq0\,.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly the asymptotic expansion breaks down when 
\begin_inset Formula $b\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

.
 The existence of this root is entirely do to gravity.
 Thus in the leading order in 
