\begin_layout Section
Conclusions and Discussion 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The new oscillatory state of cosmological matter corresponds to a limit
 cycle of the classical equations of motion.
 This state can also be considered as a cosmological realization of a time-cryst
al.
 This regime can be of interest to cosmology, because on average the universe
 undergoes the de Sitter expansion with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle w\right\rangle =-1$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, a time-crystal can be used to model early stages of Inflation or
 late stages of Dark Energy.
 We have shown that any realization of the new oscillatory state of cosmological
 matter requires not only a violation of the NEC but also a crossing of
 the Phantom Divide.
 The systems studied in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bains:2015gpv"

\end_inset

 are known to be incapable to achieve this crossing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vikman:2004dc"

\end_inset

, see also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hu:2004kh,Caldwell:2005ai,Xia:2007km"

\end_inset

 and for a review 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cai:2009zp,Nesseris:2006er"

\end_inset

.
 In particular, the crossing generically implies gradient instabilities
 where the sound speed is imaginary, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{s}^{2}<0$
\end_inset

.
 We have showed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Refreshing-k-essence-and"

\end_inset

 that the quantum perturbations of k-essence on short scales grow without
 any bound in an attempt to evolve across 
\begin_inset Formula $w=-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "sec:General-phase-space"

\end_inset

 we used the Bendixson–Dulac theorem to prove that for k-essence i) to realize
 a cosmological limit cycle classically the system has to have a flat-space
 Hamiltonian with cusps and that ii) the existence of a limit cycle implies
 that the system has a singularity where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}$
\end_inset

 changes sign and where the canonical momentum does not define the velocity
 uniquely.
 The appearance of this singularity implies the presence of configurations
 with strong superluminal propagation of the small perturbations and existence
 of other configurations with strong gradient instability.
 On this singularity the small quantum perturbations are infinitely strongly
 coupled.
 The Bendixson–Dulac theorem dictates that the singularity curve on which
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{,X}$
\end_inset

 is vanishing, should be located inside of the limit cycle, as the latter
 cannot cross the singularity.
 For some systems, including the one studied in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bains:2015gpv"

\end_inset

, the configurations with superluminality are separated from the limit cycle
 by the singularity curve with infinitely strongly coupled perturbations.
 Thus one can consider that the oscillatory solution and the superluminal
 configurations are described by two separate EFT's.
 There are arguments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Adams:2006sv"

\end_inset

 that the presence of superluminality implies that the system cannot be
 UV-completed in the usual local and Lorentz-invariant way.
 If the superluminal configurations should be described by a disconnected
 EFT different from the one which describes the limit cycle and neighboring
 configurations these arguments would not apply.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "sec:Particular_Model"

\end_inset

 we analyzed in details the dynamics of the particular class of k-essence
 models from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bains:2015gpv"

\end_inset

.
 These theories have three free parameters.
 Following the spirit of the Poincare-Bendixson theorem we analyzed for
 which values of the parameters the limit cycle is possible.
 This section serves for the illustrative purposes of our analytical results
 from the previous sections.
 We provide numerically obtained phase plots for a better visualization.
 In this particular class of theories the configurations with the superluminalit
y are always screened by the singularity from the time-crystal or limit
 cycle.
 However, the latter is also disconnected from the trivial Lorentz-invariant
 vacuum.
 Hence the EFT describing the time-crystal does not have any Lorentz-invariant
 solutions.
 It is interesting to understand under which conditions this feature allows
 for the theory to have a Lorentz-invariant and local UV-completion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The models which can violate NEC and can cross the Phantom Divide without
 immediate pathologies are Generalized Galileons / Horndeski theories 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Horndeski,Deffayet:2011gz,Kobayashi:2011nu"

\end_inset

.
 Recently it has been argued 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Libanov:2016kfc"

\end_inset

 that for the subclass of these theories introduced in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Deffayet:2010qz"

\end_inset

 it is still rather hard to have a singularity free cosmological evolution
 without any pathology and with an NEC-violating phase.
 Further these results were generalized to whole class of Horndeski theories
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kobayashi:2016xpl"

\end_inset

.
 Both these works only consider external matter which does not have any
 direct coupling to the considered Galileon scalar field.
 May be a presence of an additional degree of freedom particularly coupled
 to the Galileon can ameliorate the problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To conclude, we find the idea of cosmological time-crystals rather interesting,
 but it seems to be very hard to realize this idea in a physically plausible
 way.
 
